Depending on the rules about how magic works in a given world, you might be out of luck, fren.

>magic is OP
>magic can do absolutely anything
>why isn't everybody doing it, then?

Fantasy authors and the guys who write RPG rulebooks had to come up with something to nerf magic and mages, in order to explain why the existence of magic doesn't immediately result in everyone studying it, and skipping directly from pseudo-medieval ("'E must be a king." "'Ow can you tell?" "'E ain't got shit on 'im.") to Crystal Spires and Togas sci-fi utopia. The common thing they come up with is that most people can't do it, however much they apply themselves. It can be the Jack Vance concept, where all magic can be thought of as wishes carried out by malevolent alien genies from another dimension, and if you aren't an IQ 200 autist, capable of specifying all the correct terms on the fly, in their language, they'll fuck you up with a quickness. It can be the Tolkien concept, where magic is part of the power of the Gods, and only the Elves, who are a vanishing, dying people, and the Gods themselves can do it, and their powers with it are minor. The Terry Pratchett version is that plus "mages are assholes." Gandalf could shoot thunderbolts out of his asshole because he was one of the Maia, a god himself, in disguise. And there is the Steve Jackson Games method, where you can't do magic unless you buy the Magery attribute when you create the character, which is so expensive that after you buy it you have little choice but to make your character a squishy one-HP wonder who can only do one useful thing, and while most adventuring parties have one mage, the notes in the book say that Magery occurs "in the wild" at a rate of maybe one in ten thousand people, or less. The Lovecraft version is "you're a caveman and magic is six-dimensional fire. Are you sure you want to fuck with it? Oh, and using it will get the attention of Things from Beyond that want to eat your face."

That's sort of like Jack Vance's fantasy writing. A mage cannot command the fundamental forces of the universe by himself. Rather he summons beings with evocative, exotic-sounding names, that are never described in any detail--a Vance hallmark, his worlds are filled with wondrous imaginative strangeness--and by means never described, makes contracts with them that allow him to command them. These beings--sandestins, elementals, daihaks, and more--can be thought of as alien genies. Their minds are completely alien. They do not have sufficient grasp of, or interest in, the way humans think or what we would consider reasonable to have that quality we label common sense. They are literal-minded and malevolent, and if there is a way they can follow your directions to the letter and destroy the item you wanted them to get for you, or even kill you, they will. They are alien, but intelligent, resourceful, and imaginative, and bound only by the letter of your agreement with them, the letter of your command. One slip in dealing with them can be fatal. Mages, therefore, in the various settings--Vance wrote lots of fantasy, some set in a dying world in the far future where the sun is going out and most of humanity has either died off or fled to the stars, leaving a handful alive in a crumbling, quasi-medieval world that has forgotten everything but magic and swordplay. A trilogy of his novels were set in the mythical land of Lyonesse, which he made into an Ireland-sized island sitting in the Cantabrian Gulf roughly centered between Galicia, Ireland, and Devonshire, but the sandestins were in it too, and the mages were, as in the Dying Earth stories, mainly various flavors of assholes and maniacs, because no one else even tries dealing with sandestins and such. Other than people who were immediately killed by the spirits they tried to summon, anyway.
